### 5.2A FOOD SCALE EXAGGERATION / HERO PROP SCALE

When the composition benefits from stronger thumbnail impact, allow the food item in the subject’s hand to appear intentionally oversized.

The goal is **thumbnail-style scale drama**, not realism for realism’s sake.

#### CORE RULE

- Use food scale exaggeration selectively, not in every image
- The food item may appear noticeably larger than normal relative to the hand and body
- Prefer **forced perspective** over surreal distortion:
  - hand extended toward camera
  - food slightly closer to camera than the face
  - face and torso slightly farther back
- The food should read as the **hero prop** of the frame

#### BEST USE CASES

Use this when the image needs stronger:

- proof
- temptation
- disgust
- absurdity
- junk-food overload
- “LOOK AT THIS” energy
- thumbnail click appeal

Best scenarios:

- subject presenting a bad lunch item toward camera
- subject comparing weak vs better food options
- subject exposing an obvious lunch mistake
- subject holding one clear proof object that should dominate the frame

#### PROPORTION CONTROL

- Exaggerate the food to roughly **120%–180% of normal perceived size**
- Keep the hand anatomy natural and believable
- Do **not** make fingers swollen, fused, bent incorrectly, or unnaturally stretched
- Do **not** deform the wrist or grip just to force the item into frame
- The item should feel oversized in a **thumbnail way**, not bizarre or surreal unless explicitly requested

#### COMPOSITION RULES

- Use only **one oversized hero food object** per image unless a comparison layout requires two
- The oversized item must remain clearly readable and separated from the background
- The oversized item should not fully block the face or key expression
- If the food is the main proof object, it should visually dominate more than secondary props
- Keep the gesture simple and readable: one clear hand, one clear item, one clear focal purpose

#### TEXT + CALLOUT INTERACTION

- Do **not** place the HOOK_TEXT over the oversized hero food object
- If using an arrow, circle, X, or checkmark with the hero prop, use **fewer** callouts, not more
- Prefer one clean callout on the oversized item rather than stacking multiple symbols on it

